Neural Network Reggresion 

library(neuralnet)
library(knitr)
library(nnet)
library(kableExtra)
library(dplyr)
concrete<-read.csv("Concrete_Data.csv")

normalize<-function(x){
  return((x - min(x))/(max(x)-min(x)))
}
DT::datatable(concrete[-6,-7],options=list(pageLength = 5))
concrete_norm<-as.data.frame(lapply(concrete,normalize))
summary(concrete_norm$CC_strength)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0000  0.2664  0.4001  0.4172  0.5457  1.0000
n = nrow(concrete_norm)
trainIndex = sample(1:n, size = round(0.7*n), replace=FALSE)
train = concrete_norm[trainIndex ,]
test = concrete_norm[-trainIndex ,]

model<-neuralnet(target~ predictors,data=data,hidden=n)
hidden is the number of neurons in the hidden layer.
predictions<-compute(model,test) -> predictions$net.result function gives the results of model.

concrete_model<-neuralnet(CC_strength~., data=train,hidden = 10)

predicted<-predict(concrete_model,test[1:8])
cor(predicted,test$CC_strength)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.9470916
nn_model<-nnet(CC_strength~., data=train, size=10, decay=5e-5, maxit=1000)
predicted_nn<-predict(nn_model,test[1:8])
cor(predicted_nn,test$CC_strength)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.9420967

Support Vector Machines Algorithm on Letter Prediction 

library(kernlab)
library(arules)

ksvm(x, y = NULL, scaled = TRUE, type = NULL, kernel =rbfdot, kpar = automatic, C = 1, nu = 0.2, epsilon = 0.1, prob.model = FALSE, class.weights = NULL, cross = 0, fit = TRUE, cache = 40, tol = 0.001, shrinking = TRUE, , subset, na.action = na.omit)

predictions<-predict(model,test,type=response or probabilities )

letters<-read.csv("letterdata.csv")
plot(as.data.frame(table(letters$letter)))

n = nrow(letters)
trainIndex = sample(1:n, size = round(0.7*n), replace=FALSE)
letters_train = letters[trainIndex ,]
letters_test = letters[-trainIndex ,]
DT::datatable(letters[1:6])
letter_classifier<-ksvm(letter~.,data=letters_train,kernel="vanilladot")
##  Setting default kernel parameters
letter_predictions<-predict(letter_classifier,letters_test)
head(letter_predictions)

The LHS is the condition that needs to be met in order to trigger the rule, and the RHS is the expected result of meeting that condition.

The lift values tells about us how much more likely a customer is to buy product relative to the average customer,given that he or she bought another product.

inspect(sort(groceryrules,by="lift")[1:5])
##     lhs                   rhs                      support confidence     lift count
